				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225880" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1449402845 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">06 Dec 2015 11:54</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2418282">
									

<p>I'm conflicted on this tale. On the one hand, I enjoy the interpretation, behaviour, and presented origin of the Oneiroi. I think the contrast between their view of the end of their civilization and the Foundation's provided an interesting narrative.</p>
<p>On the other hand, the interpretation of SCP-990 felt like providing a relatively mundane, unsatisfying answer to what was originally a quite entertaining mystery. It didn't help that this tale often found ways to jettison elements of 990 (the appearance, the high-numbered SCP) rather than incorporate them. For example, the change in the iconic appearance mostly came across as an excuse to use a different cool picture.</p>
<p>Given the deliberate pinning down of the mystery, the reversion to a state of uncertainty at the end felt a little cheap.</p>
<p>I still enjoyed certain elements of that narrative, including the multiversal Foundation callously experimenting with human extinction and the potential categorization of the operative as anomalous. Even with that, I can't help but see this interpretation as a downgrade to the original. No vote.</p>

							</div>

								
					
